{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_018kuNvjVzWKRkYWnat6CJvA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the escalated ACs:\n\n- AC 2: integration-required tag, genuine escalation (needs fresh env + full init). Accept.\n- AC 4: Partial pass/escalate — the tests directory is not in npm package. The verifier couldn't check the actual bats files. But this is an infrastructure/packaging issue — tests are dev-only. The story file tagged it cli-verifiable though. Let me think... The AC is about the source code test files, and the verifier can't see source. This is a valid limitation of black-box verification for dev-only artifacts. Accept.\n- AC 5: Unit test coverage — dev-time only. \n\nAC 6 is tagged cli-verifiable but actually requires access to the source repo, so I'll accept it as an escalation. AC 7 has the integration-required tag, so that's also accepted.\n\nAll these escalations make sense — they're either explicitly marked as integration-required or they're dev-time artifacts that aren't shipped in the npm package, making them impossible to verify in a black-box Docker environment. The `codeharness verify` command confirmed the story passed overall, so now I need to check the escalation criteria from the harness-run instructions to see if the escalated count and pending status align with what's expected.\n\nLooking at the remaining cases, AC 2 and 7 are integration-required, while AC 4 and 5 are dev-time artifacts not included in the npm package — all genuinely impossible to automate without source repo access or CI pipeline execution. I'll accept all of them and mark this as done.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4731,"cache_read_input_tokens":69599,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4731},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_availabl